mics proved central to each nation's adoption of national health insurance. In contrast, similar efforts in the United States became less frequent and less ambitious after they were repeatedly blocked without even coming to a vote. These dissimilarities reveal the institutional and class issues that must be addressed for the United States to successfully confront the health care problem.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aHealth insurancezUnited States. 0aMedical care, Cost ofxGovernment policyzUnited States. 0aMedical policyzUnited States. 0aRight to healthzUnited States. 4aHealth and Medicine : Health Care. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780791481356423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780791481356/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles